# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wasm-component-model
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] An **application binary interface** (**ABI**) is an interface exposed by software that is defined for in-process machine code access.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] Often, the exposing software is a library, and the consumer is a program.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] An ABI is at a relatively low level of abstraction.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] Interface compatibility depends on the target hardware and the software build toolchain.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] In contrast, an application programming interface (API) defines access in source code, which is a relatively high-level, hardware-independent, and human-readable format.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] An API defines an interface at the source code level, before compilation, whereas an ABI defines an interface to compiled code.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] API compatibility is generally the concern for system design and of the toolchain.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] However, a programmer may have to deal with an ABI directly when writing a program in multiple languages or when using multiple compilers for the same language.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] A complete ABI enables a program that supports an ABI to run without modification on multiple operating systems that provide the ABI.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] The target system must provide any required libraries (that implement the ABI), and there may be other prerequisites.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] ABIs include the Intel Binary Compatibility Standard (iBCS) and the System V Release 4 ABIs for various instruction sets.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] An **embedded ABI** (**EABI**), used on an embedded operating system, specifies aspects such as file formats, data types, register usage, stack frame organization, and function parameter passing of an embedded software program.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] Each compiler and assembler that supports an EABI creates object code that is compatible with code generated by other such compilers and assemblers.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] This allows developers to link libraries generated by one compiler with object code generated by another.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] Typically, an EABI is optimized for performance for the limited resources of the target embedded system.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] Therefore, an EABI may omit abstractions between kernel and user space typically found in desktop operating systems.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] The choice of EABI can affect performance.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] Widely used EABIs include the PowerPC, Arm, and MIPS EABIs.
[src:wasm-component-model/application-binary-interface] Specific software implementations like the C library may impose additional limitations to form more concrete ABIs; one example is the GNU OABI and EABI for ARM, both of which are subsets of the ARM EABI.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] The WebAssembly Component Model is a broad-reaching architecture for building interoperable WebAssembly libraries, applications, and environments.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] This documentation is aimed at *users* of the component model: developers of libraries and applications.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] As with all programming, the goal of writing a component is to make new functionality available by building it out of existing functionality.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] A WebAssembly component runs on a *platform*, which may be a Web browser, a stand-alone runtime, or even an operating system (when compiling WebAssembly to an executable).
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] By running the component, the platform gains the functionality that the component implements.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] Likewise, the platform provides functionality that code in components can use to interact with the outside world.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] In general, a platform that runs components must provide well-defined APIs for accessing functionality that components need: for example, reading from standard input, accessing environment variables, or manipulating network sockets.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] It’s useful to have a standard, shared set of APIs that WebAssembly components can depend on.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] WASI (the WebAssembly System Interface) is a standards-track specification that defines these APIs.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] A system or platform may expose some or all of the WASI APIs to components.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] The current stable release of WASI is WASI 0.2.0, which was released on January 25, 2024.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] WASI 0.2.0 is a stable set of WIT definitions that components can target.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] WASI proposals will continue to evolve and new ones will be introduced; however, users of the component model can now pin to any stable release >= `v0.2.0`.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] The WASI.dev roadmap tracks upcoming releases.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] If you find a mistake, omission, ambiguity, or other problem, please let us know via GitHub issues.
[src:wasm-component-model/component-model-bytecodealliance-org] If you’d like to contribute content to the guide, please see the contribution guide for information on how to contribute.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] In computing, an **interface** is a shared boundary across which two or more separate components of a computer system exchange information.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] The exchange can be between software, computer hardware, peripheral devices, humans, and combinations of these.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Some computer hardware devices, such as a touchscreen, can both send and receive data through the interface, while others such as a mouse or microphone may only provide an interface to send data to a given system.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Hardware interfaces exist in many components, such as the various buses, storage devices, other I/O devices, etc.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] A hardware interface is described by the mechanical, electrical, and logical signals at the interface and the protocol for sequencing them (sometimes called signaling).
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] A standard interface, such as SCSI, decouples the design and introduction of computing hardware, such as I/O devices, from the design and introduction of other components of a computing system, thereby allowing users and manufacturers great flexibility in the implementation of computing systems.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Hardware interfaces can be parallel with several electrical connections carrying parts of the data simultaneously or serial where data are sent one bit at a time.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] A software interface may refer to a wide range of different types of interfaces at different "levels".
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] For example, an operating system may interface with pieces of hardware.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Applications or programs running on the operating system may need to interact via data streams, filters, and pipelines.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] In object oriented programs, objects within an application may need to interact via methods.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] A key principle of design is to prohibit access to all resources by default, allowing access only through well-defined entry points, i.e., interfaces.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Interfaces between software components can provide constants, data types, types of procedures, exception specifications, and method signatures.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Sometimes, public variables are also defined as part of an interface.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] The interface of a software module *A* is deliberately defined separately from the implementation of that module.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] The latter contains the actual code of the procedures and methods described in the interface, as well as other "private" variables, procedures, etc.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Another software module *B*, for example the client to *A*, that interacts with *A* is forced to do so only through the published interface.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] In some object-oriented languages, especially those without full multiple inheritance, the term *interface* is used to define an abstract type that acts as an abstraction of a class.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] It contains no data, but defines behaviours as method signatures.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] A class having code and data for all the methods corresponding to that interface and declaring so is said to *implement* that interface.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Furthermore, even in single-inheritance-languages, one can implement multiple interfaces, and hence can *be* of different types at the same time.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] An interface is thus a type definition; anywhere an object can be exchanged (for example, in a function or method call) the *type* of the object to be exchanged can be defined in terms of one of its implemented *interface*s or base-classes rather than specifying the specific class.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] This approach means that any class that implements that interface can be used.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] For example, a dummy implementation may be used to allow development to progress before the final implementation is available.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] In another case, a fake or mock implementation may be substituted during testing.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Such stub implementations are replaced by real code later in the development process.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Usually, a method defined in an interface contains no code and thus cannot itself be called; it must be implemented by non-abstract code to be run when it is invoked.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] An interface called "`Stack`" might define two methods: `push()` and `pop()`.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] It can be implemented in different ways, for example, `FastStack` and `GenericStack`—the first being fast, working with a data structure of fixed size, and the second using a data structure that can be resized, but at the cost of somewhat lower speed.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Though interfaces can contain many methods, they may contain only one or even none at all.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] For example, the Java language defines the interface `Readable` that has the single `read()` method; various implementations are used for different purposes, including `BufferedReader`, `FileReader`, `InputStreamReader`, `PipedReader`, and `StringReader`.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Marker interfaces like `Serializable` contain no methods at all and serve to provide run-time information to generic processing using Reflection.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] The use of interfaces allows for a programming style called *programming to the interface*.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] The idea behind this approach is to base programming logic on the interfaces of the objects used, rather than on internal implementation details.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Programming to the interface reduces dependency on implementation specifics and makes code more reusable.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] Pushing this idea to the extreme, inversion of control leaves the *context* to inject the code with the specific implementations of the interface that will be used to perform the work.
[src:wasm-component-model/interface-computing] A **user interface** is a point of interaction between a computer and humans; it includes any number of modalities of interaction (such as graphics, sound, position, movement, etc.) where data is transferred between the user and the computer system.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:wasm-component-model/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:wasm-component-model/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
